// test activity The IGD-20 Test
// begin test activity Begin Test" The IGD-20 test is a test developed in order to assess an individuals level of internet gaming addiction (The American Psychiatric Association). Preoccupation with video gaming. Irritability, anxiety, or stress when not gaming. Increasingly amounts of time spent gaming in order to achieve satisfaction. Difficult to reduce gaming time. Interests and hobbies lost as a result of gaming. Gaming habits cause conflict between you and other people. Deceiving people about the amount of gaming done. Gaming done in order to escape negative feelings such as guilt, stress, or helplessness. Jeopardized a relationship, job, or career opportunity because of gaming.
// about activity According to the American Psychiatric Association, Internet Gaming Disorder is a disorder characterized by nine criteria: preoccupation with gaming, withdrawal symptoms, the need to play to satisfy urges, inability to reduce playing time, giving up other activities, continuing to game despite problems, deceiving family members about amount of playing time, the use of video games to avoid negative feelings, and risk, having jeopardized or lost jobs or relationships due to gaming. This application provides users with a tool based on these nine criteria to assess an internet gaming addiction.
// quiz activity I often lose sleep because of long gaming sessions. I never play games in order to feel better. I have significantly increased the amount of time I play games over last year. When I am not gaming I feel more irritable. I have lost interest in other hobbies because of my gaming. I would like to cut down my gaming time but it’s difficult to do. I usually think about my next gaming session when I am not playing. I play games to help me cope with any bad feelings I might have. I need to spend increasing amounts of time engaged in playing games. I feel sad if I am not able to play games. I have lied to my family members because the amount of gaming I do. I do not think I could stop gaming. I think gaming has become the most time consuming activity in my life. I play games to forget about whatever’s bothering me. I often think that a whole day is not enough to do everything I need to do in-game. I tend to get anxious if I can’t play games for any reason. I think my gaming has jeopardized the relationship with my partner. I often try to play games less but find I cannot. I know my main daily activity has not been negatively affected by my gaming. (i.e., occupation, education, homemaker, etc.) I believe my gaming is negatively impacting on important areas of my life. Submit Strongly Agree Agree Not Sure Disagree Strongly Disagree
// test results activity Test Results The IGD-20 test, also known as the Internet Gaming Disorder-20 test, was developed by the American Psychiatric Association based on a six factors: salience, mood modification, tolerance, withdrawal symptoms, conflict, and relapse. Below with help further your understanding of your IGD-20 score. Preoccuption with Internet games. The individual thinks about previous gaming activity or anticipates playing the next game; Internet gaming becomes the dominant activity in daily life. Use of Internet games to escape or relieve a negative mood (eg., feelings of helplessness, guilt, anxiety). The need to spend increasing amounts of time engaged in Internet games. Withdrawal symptoms when Internet gaming is taken away. These symptoms are typically described as irritability, anxiety, or sadness, but are no physical signs of pharmacological withdrawal. Loss of interests in previous hobbies and entertainment as a result of, and with the exception of, Internet Games. Continued excessive use of Internet games despite knowledge of psychosocial problems. Has deceived family members, therapists, or others regarding the amount of Internet gaming. Has jeopardised or lost a significant relationship, job, or educational career opportunity because of participation in Internet games. Unsuccessful attempts to control the participation in Internet games. Individuals in this category scored low on all the six factors of described above (salience, mood modification, tolerance, withdrawal symptoms, conflict, and relapse. This class also classifies gamers that scored low on the six dimensions. One difference however, is that regular gamers score higher on the mood modification factor. This means individuals often play to avoid negative feelings such as stress or anxiety. Low-risk high engagement gamers that often play more than the regular gamer. Alike regular gamers, individuals in this class often play to feel better. These gamers also may have a strong urge to play video games when they are not. Individuals may find it difficult to reduce play time. Individuals are more preoccupied with video games and it becomes the main activity in everyday life. This may lead to loss in interests and hobbies. Tolerance increases as individuals feel the need to spend increasing amounts time playing games. Unlike low-risk high engagement gamers, conflict and relapse factors are much lower. Disordered gamers are individuals that scored high on all six dimensions of the IGD test. Gaming is the main activity in life and at this point, it is very difficult to cut down playing time. Conflicts in everyday life are more likely than not related to video gaming.
